

# ðŸ§© Length of the Largest Subarray with Continuous Elements

## âœ… Problem Summary

Given an array of **distinct integers**, find the length of the **longest subarray** such that the numbers inside that subarray form a **continuous sequence**.

> Subarray must be **continuous index-wise**
> Values must be **continuous number-wise**

---

## ðŸ”‘ Key Observation (Core Logic)

For any subarray `arr[i â€¦ j]` to contain continuous numbers:

```
max(arr[i..j]) - min(arr[i..j]) == (j - i)
```

### Why?

If numbers are continuous like: `[5,6,7,8]`

```
max = 8
min = 5
length = 4

8 - 5 = 3 = length - 1
```

Since elements are **distinct**, this condition is enough to guarantee continuity.

---

## ðŸ’» C++ Implementation (Fully Commented)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int maxLength(int n, vector<int> &arr){

    // Minimum possible answer is 1,
    // because a single element is always a valid continuous subarray
    int ans = 1;

    // Fix the starting point of subarray
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){

        int mini = arr[i];  // smallest element in current window
        int maxi = arr[i];  // largest element in current window

        // Extend the subarray from i to j
        for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++){

            // Update minimum and maximum for this window
            mini = min(mini, arr[j]);
            maxi = max(maxi, arr[j]);

            // Check if elements between i and j are continuous
            // Condition: max - min == window size - 1
            if(maxi - mini == j - i){

                // Length of subarray = j - i + 1
                ans = max(ans, j - i + 1);
            }
        }
    }

    return ans;
}
```

---

## ðŸ§ª Detailed Dry Run

### Example Input

```
arr = [14, 12, 11, 20]
index  0    1    2    3
```

---

### â–¶ i = 0 (start from 14)

| j | Subarray      | mini | maxi | maxi-mini | j-i | Continuous? |
| - | ------------- | ---- | ---- | --------- | --- | ----------- |
| 1 | [14,12]       | 12   | 14   | 2         | 1   | âŒ           |
| 2 | [14,12,11]    | 11   | 14   | 3         | 2   | âŒ           |
| 3 | [14,12,11,20] | 11   | 20   | 9         | 3   | âŒ           |

No valid subarray from i=0

---

### â–¶ i = 1 (start from 12)

| j | Subarray   | mini | maxi | maxi-mini | j-i | Continuous? |
| - | ---------- | ---- | ---- | --------- | --- | ----------- |
| 2 | [12,11]    | 11   | 12   | 1         | 1   | âœ…           |
| 3 | [12,11,20] | 11   | 20   | 9         | 2   | âŒ           |

Valid subarray: `[12,11]` â†’ length = **2**

`ans = 2`

---

### â–¶ i = 2 (start from 11)

| j | Subarray | mini | maxi | maxi-mini | j-i | Continuous? |
| - | -------- | ---- | ---- | --------- | --- | ----------- |
| 3 | [11,20]  | 11   | 20   | 9         | 1   | âŒ           |

---

### â–¶ i = 3

Single element â†’ already counted via `ans = 1`

---

## âœ… Final Answer = **2**

---

## ðŸ§  Why `ans = 1` initially?

Even if no pair forms a continuous sequence, **any single element** is always valid.

---

## ðŸ§  Why `j - i + 1`?

Length of subarray formula:

```
length = ending index - starting index + 1
```

---

## â± Complexity

| Type  | Value |
| ----- | ----- |
| Time  | O(nÂ²) |
| Space | O(1)  |

Works smoothly for `n â‰¤ 5000`.

